                        <tr>
                          <td width="100%"><font face="Verdana" size="2"><b>Salalah hotel
                            industry<br>
                            How green is my valley?</b></font>
                            <p><font face="Verdana" size="2">The hotel industry in Salalah is a mixed bag. It is an industry that was built on natural attractions and was expected to grow further based on man-made amenities. But just as Salalah's pleasant weather, archaeological sites and Khareef festival had started putting the Sultanate on the world tourist map, the impact of 9/11 and delays in certain major projects locally has left the hotel industry to survive on its
                            own.<br>
                            Salalah, which forms the main agricultural belt of the Sultanate, hosts the country's largest port facility - the Salalah Port Services
                            (SPS) SAOG. Added to this is the much-talked-about Salalah Free Trade Zone
                            (SFTZ) that has been prone to undue delays. Hoteliers cite the postponement of SFTZ as the main reason for the hotel industry to report moderate and, at times, descending growth; plus the woes continue for the industry owing to low tourists
                            turnout.<br>
                            Says Sayed Hassan, general manager, Crowne Plaza Resort Salalah (Holiday Inn
                            Salalah), "Even though there is a slight growth in tourism in the past two years during the Khareef (monsoon) season, the European tourism to Salalah (between October to April) has shown a downward trend mainly due to the uncertainties prevalent in the Middle East."<br>
 Striking a different note, Franz Josef Macho, general manager, Hilton Salalah explains that many hotel establishments, including Hilton, were built after the plan for constructing the SFTZ was conceived by the government.
                            "This newly created capacity within the hotel industry was supposed to largely service the corporate business originating from
                            SFTZ. However, the delay in this project has left hotel establishments to look out for new avenues," he
                            says.<br>
                            As far as business from SPS is concerned hoteliers have displayed mixed observations, but most of them do agree that a lot more needs to be done to ensure immediate and long-term growth of the city. Hassan of Crowne Plaza feels that the opening of SPS has not really contributed to any corporate business, whereas Macho from Hilton argues that SPS does generate good business, and stresses that (sometimes) corporate business has been exceeding than tourism.<br>
  To this, Jack Helton, chief executive officer of SPS, says that economic growth in Salalah is dependent upon immediate tourism development. He acknowledges that any further delay in the development of Salalah's free zone would have an adverse knock-on effect on the business in the city including that of SPS and hospitality companies. As part of the government's masterplan for
                            Dhofar, the free zone is intended to be created alongside other infrastructure projects such as Salalah Airport, he adds.&nbsp;<br>
 Talking about tourism, hoteliers opine that there is still a long way to go. One of the major hindrances facing the development of the tourism sector in Salalah is the non-availability of direct flights into the city. Passengers often have to take long transits at Muscat and airport, as many of them say, needs a drastic facelift. Hotels like Hilton, in order to avoid losing out on passengers, are offering tourists to spend a few days in Dubai, before coming down to
                            Salalah. "Lack of direct flights to Salalah from major European hubs and high airfares also contribute to the downward trend," says one source.<br>
 Industry players also suggest that hotels in Salalah cannot do much more than what they are already doing.
                            "What is required is development of more infrastructure facilities geared towards tourists in the Dhofar Region, like cable cars linking the mountains, public toilets, public transport, high quality mountain restaurants, direct flights from major European hubs and GCC destinations to
                            Salalah," says Hassan of Crowne Plaza.<br>
                            The efforts of the Directorate of Tourism towards promoting tourism do help in getting more tourists.  However, the hotels have to undertake their own promotions as these complement each other to achieve the overall goal of increasing tourism traffic to the Sultanate. Here also, hotels like Hilton benefit through their vast network (more than 2,400 establishments) across the globe, and Crowne Plaza, through the central reservation system of Six Continents promotes itself and the destination.<br>
 As far as the profile of guests is concerned, hotels receive guests mainly from other GCC countries during the Khareef festival. Most of them also receive guests from Europe (mainly from Germany). High-spending tourist is also on the move in Oman and hotels are seen upgrading their premises. And most of the hotels do make their own sales trips to various GCC countries for promoting the monsoon season in addition to tying up with airlines, tour operators and travel
                            agents.&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></td>
                        </tr>
